{"type":"session_message","session_id":"ses_28a4be054ffe9NRt4aphiycBPg","role":"assistant","message_id":"msg_d75b4348d001ZapnREv63UT0ms","parts":[{"id":"prt_d75b4411d001Ve1fDSq5QrPecZ","messageID":"msg_d75b4348d001ZapnREv63UT0ms","sessionID":"ses_28a4be054ffe9NRt4aphiycBPg","type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_a8b973e6127940e08beede38","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/workspace/docs/getting_started.md"},"output":"<path>/workspace/docs/getting_started.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>1: ---\n2: title: Getting Started\n3: description: A short tutorial on installing the software and running a simple benchmark.\n4: ---\n5: \n6: # Getting Started\n7: \n8: The AutoML Benchmark is a tool for benchmarking AutoML frameworks on tabular data.\n9: It automates the installation of AutoML frameworks, passing it data, and evaluating\n10: their predictions.\n11: [Our paper](https://arxiv.org/pdf/2207.12560.pdf) describes the design and showcases\n12: results from an evaluation using the benchmark.\n13: This guide goes over the minimum steps needed to evaluate an\n14: AutoML framework on a toy dataset.\n15: \n16: ## Installation\n17: These instructions assume that [Python 3.9 (or higher)](https://www.python.org/downloads/)\n18: and [git](https://git-scm.com/book/en/v2/Getting-Started-Installing-Git) are installed,\n19: and are available under the alias `python` and `git`, respectively. We recommend\n20: [Pyenv](https://github.com/pyenv/pyenv) for managing multiple Python installations,\n21: if applicable. We support Ubuntu 22.04, but many linux and MacOS versions likely work\n22: (for MacOS, it may be necessary to have [`brew`](https://brew.sh) installed).\n23: \n24: First, clone the repository:\n25: \n26: ```bash\n27: git clone https://github.com/openml/automlbenchmark.git --branch stable --depth 1\n28: cd automlbenchmark\n29: ```\n30: \n31: Create a virtual environments to install the dependencies in:\n32: \n33: === \":simple-linux: Linux\"\n34: \n35:     ```bash\n36:     python -m venv venv\n37:     source venv/bin/activate\n38:     ```\n39: \n40: === \":material-apple: MacOS\"\n41: \n42:     ```bash\n43:     python -m venv venv\n44:     source venv/bin/activate\n45:     ```\n46: \n47: === \":simple-windows: Windows\"\n48: \n49:     ```bash\n50:     python -m venv ./venv\n51:     venv/Scripts/activate\n52:     ```\n53: \n54: Then install the dependencies:\n55: \n56: ```bash\n57: python -m pip install --upgrade pip\n58: python -m pip install -r requirements.txt\n59: ```\n60: \n61: \n62: ??? windows \"Note for Windows users\"\n63: \n64:     The automated installation of AutoML frameworks is done using shell script,\n65:     which doesn't work on Windows. We recommend you use\n66:     [Docker](https://docs.docker.com/desktop/install/windows-install/) to run the\n67:     examples below. First, install and run `docker`.\n68:     Then, whenever there is a `python runbenchmark.py ...`\n69:     command in the tutorial, add `-m docker` to it (`python runbenchmark.py ... -m docker`).\n70: \n71: ??? question \"Problem with the installation?\"\n72: \n73:     On some platforms, we need to ensure that requirements are installed sequentially.\n74:     Use `xargs -L 1 python -m pip install < requirements.txt` to do so. If problems\n75:     persist, [open an issue](https://github.com/openml/automlbenchmark/issues/new) with\n76:     the error and information about your environment (OS, Python version, pip version).\n77: \n78: \n79: ## Running the Benchmark\n80: \n81: To run a benchmark call the `runbenchmark.py` script specifying the framework to evaluate.\n82: See [integrated frameworks](WEBSITE/frameworks.html) for a list of supported frameworks, or the [adding a frameworking](extending/framework.md) page on how to add your own.\n83: \n84: ### Example: a test run with Random Forest\n85: Let's try evaluating the `RandomForest` baseline, which uses [scikit-learn](https://scikit-learn.org/stable/)'s random forest:\n86: \n87: === \":simple-linux: Linux\"\n88: \n89:     ```bash\n90:     python runbenchmark.py randomforest\n91:     ```\n92: \n93: === \":material-apple: MacOS\"\n94: \n95:     ```bash\n96:     python runbenchmark.py randomforest\n97:     ```\n98: \n99: === \":simple-windows: Windows\"\n100:     As noted above, we need to install the AutoML frameworks (and baselines) in\n101:     a container. Add `-m docker` to the command as shown:\n102:     ```bash\n103:     python runbenchmark.py randomforest -m docker\n104:     ```\n105: \n106:     !!! warning \"Important\"\n107:         Future example usages will only show invocations without `-m docker` mode,\n108:         but Windows users will need to run in some non-local mode.\n109: \n110: After running the command, there will be a lot of output to the screen that reports\n111: on what is currently happening. After a few minutes final results are shown and should\n112: look similar to this:\n113: \n114: ```\n115: Summing up scores for current run:\n116:                id        task  fold    framework constraint     result      metric  duration      seed\n117: openml.org/t/3913         kc2     0 RandomForest       test   0.865801         auc      11.1 851722466\n118: openml.org/t/3913         kc2     1 RandomForest       test   0.857143         auc       9.1 851722467\n119:   openml.org/t/59        iris     0 RandomForest       test  -0.120755 neg_logloss       8.7 851722466\n120:   openml.org/t/59        iris     1 RandomForest       test  -0.027781 neg_logloss       8.5 851722467\n121: openml.org/t/2295 cholesterol     0 RandomForest       test -44.220800    neg_rmse       8.7 851722466\n122: openml.org/t/2295 cholesterol     1 RandomForest       test -55.216500    neg_rmse       8.7 851722467\n123: ```\n124: \n125: The result denotes the performance of the framework on the test data as measured by\n126: the metric listed in the metric column. The result column always denotes performance\n127: in a way where higher is better (metrics which normally observe \"lower is better\" are\n128: converted, which can be observed from the `neg_` prefix).\n129: \n130: While running the command, the AutoML benchmark performed the following steps:\n131: \n132:  1. Create a new virtual environment for the Random Forest experiment.\n133:     This environment can be found in `frameworks/randomforest/venv` and will be re-used\n134:     when you perform other experiments with `RandomForest`.\n135:  2. It downloaded datasets from [OpenML](https://www.openml.org) complete with a\n136:     \"task definition\" which specifies [cross-validation](https://scikit-learn.org/stable/modules/cross_validation.html) folds.\n137:  3. It evaluated `RandomForest` on each (task, fold)-combination in a separate subprocess, where:\n138:     1. The framework (`RandomForest`) is initialized.\n139:     2. The training data is passed to the framework for training.\n140:     3. The test data is passed to the framework to make predictions on.\n141:     4. It passes the predictions back to the main process\n142:  4. The predictions are evaluated and reported on. They are printed to the console and\n143:     are stored in the `results` directory. There you will find:\n144:     1. `results/results.csv`: a file with all results from all benchmarks conducted on your machine.\n145:     2. `results/randomforest.test.test.local.TIMESTAMP`: a directory with more information about the run,\n146:         such as logs, predictions, and possibly other artifacts.\n147: \n148: !!! info \"Docker Mode\"\n149: \n150:     When using docker mode (with `-m docker`) a docker image will be made that contains\n151:     the virtual environment. Otherwise, it functions much the same way.\n152: \n153: ### Important Parameters\n154: \n155: As you can see from the results above, the  default behavior is to execute a short test\n156: benchmark. However, we can specify a different benchmark, provide different constraints,\n157: and even run the experiment in a container or on AWS. There are many parameters\n158: for the `runbenchmark.py` script, but the most important ones are:\n159: \n160: `Framework (required)`\n161: \n162: : The AutoML framework or baseline to evaluate and is not case-sensitive. See\n163:   [integrated frameworks](WEBSITE/frameworks.html) for a list of supported frameworks.\n164:   In the above example, this benchmarked framework `randomforest`.\n165: \n166: `Benchmark (optional, default='test')`\n167: \n168: : The benchmark suite is the dataset or set of datasets to evaluate the framework on.\n169:   These can be defined as on [OpenML](https://www.openml.org) as a [study or task](extending/benchmark.md#defining-a-benchmark-on-openml)\n170:   (formatted as `openml/s/X` or `openml/t/Y` respectively) or in a [local file](extending/benchmark.md#defining-a-benchmark-with-a-file).\n171:   The default is a short evaluation on two folds of `iris`, `kc2`, and `cholesterol`.\n172: \n173: `Constraints (optional, default='test')`\n174: \n175: : The constraints applied to the benchmark as defined by default in [constraints.yaml](GITHUB/resources/constraints.yaml).\n176:   These include time constraints, memory constrains, the number of available cpu cores, and more.\n177:   Default constraint is `test` (2 folds for 10 min each).\n178: \n179:     !!! warning \"Constraints are not enforced!\"\n180:         These constraints are forwarded to the AutoML framework if possible but, except for\n181:         runtime constraints, are generally not enforced. It is advised when benchmarking\n182:         to use an environment that mimics the given constraints.\n183: \n184:     ??? info \"Constraints can be overriden by `benchmark`\"\n185:         A benchmark definition can override constraints on a task level.\n186:         This is useful if you want to define a benchmark which has different constraints\n187:         for different tasks. The default \"test\" benchmark does this to limit runtime to\n188:         60 seconds instead of 600 seconds, which is useful to get quick results for its\n189:         small datasets. For more information, see [defining a benchmark](#ADD-link-to-adding-benchmark).\n190: \n191: `Mode (optional, default='local')`\n192: \n193: :  The benchmark can be run in four modes:\n194: \n195:      * `local`: install a local virtual environment and run the benchmark on your machine.\n196:      * `docker`: create a docker image with the virtual environment and run the benchmark in a container on your machine.\n197:                  If a local or remote image already exists, that will be used instead. Requires [Docker](https://docs.docker.com/desktop/).\n198:      * `singularity`: create a singularity image with the virtual environment and run the benchmark in a container on your machine. Requires [Singularity](https://docs.sylabs.io/guides/3.5/user-guide/introduction.html).\n199:      * `aws`: run the benchmark on [AWS EC2](https://aws.amazon.com/free/?trk=b3f93e34-c1e0-4aa9-95f8-6d2c36891d8a&sc_channel=ps&ef_id=CjwKCAjw-7OlBhB8EiwAnoOEk0li05IUgU9Ok2uCdejP22Yr7ZuqtMeJZAdxgL5KZFaeOVskCAsknhoCSjUQAvD_BwE:G:s&s_kwcid=AL!4422!3!649687387631!e!!g!!aws%20ec2!19738730094!148084749082&all-free-tier.sort-by=item.additionalFields.SortRank&all-free-tier.sort-order=asc&awsf.Free%20Tier%20Types=*all&awsf.Free%20Tier%20Categories=*all) instances.\n200:               It is possible to run directly on the instance or have the EC2 instance run in `docker` mode.\n201:               Requires valid AWS credentials to be configured, for more information see [Running on AWS](#ADD-link-to-aws-guide).\n202: \n203: \n204: For a full list of parameters available, run:\n205: \n206: ```\n207: python runbenchmark.py --help\n208: ```\n209: \n210: ### Example: AutoML on a specific task and fold\n211: \n212: The defaults are very useful for performing a quick test, as the datasets are small\n213: and cover different task types (binary classification, multiclass classification, and\n214: regression). We also have a [\"validation\" benchmark](GITHUB/resources/benchmarks/validation.yaml)\n215: suite for more elaborate testing that also includes missing data, categorical data,\n216: wide data, and more. The benchmark defines 9 tasks, and evaluating two folds with a\n217: 10-minute time constraint would take roughly 3 hours (=9 tasks * 2 folds * 10 minutes,\n218: plus overhead). Let's instead use the `--task` and `--fold` parameters to run only a\n219: specific task and fold in the `benchmark` when evaluating the\n220: [flaml](https://microsoft.github.io/FLAML/) AutoML framework:\n221: \n222: ```\n223: python runbenchmark.py flaml validation test -t eucalyptus -f 0\n224: ```\n225: \n226: This should take about 10 minutes plus the time it takes to install `flaml`.\n227: Results should look roughly like this:\n228: \n229: ```\n230: Processing results for flaml.validation.test.local.20230711T122823\n231: Summing up scores for current run:\n232:                id       task  fold framework constraint    result      metric  duration       seed\n233: openml.org/t/2079 eucalyptus     0     flaml       test -0.702976 neg_logloss     611.0 1385946458\n234: ```\n235: \n236: Similarly to the test run, you will find additional files in the `results` directory.\n237: \n238: \n239: ### Example: Benchmarks on OpenML\n240: \n241: In the previous examples, we used benchmarks which were defined in a local file\n242: ([test.yaml](GITHUB/resources/benchmarks/test.yaml) and\n243: [validation.yaml](GITHUB/resources/benchmarks/validation.yaml), respectively).\n244: However, we can also use tasks and\n245: benchmarking suites defined on OpenML directly from the command line. When referencing\n246: an OpenML task or suite, we can use `openml/t/ID` or `openml/s/ID` respectively as\n247: argument for the benchmark parameter. Running on the [iris task](https://openml.org/t/59):\n248: \n249: ```\n250: python runbenchmark.py randomforest openml/t/59\n251: ```\n252: \n253: or on the entire [AutoML benchmark classification suite](https://openml.org/s/271) (this will take hours!):\n254: \n255: ```\n256: python runbenchmark.py randomforest openml/s/271\n257: ```\n258: \n259: !!! info \"Large-scale Benchmarking\"\n260: \n261:     For large scale benchmarking it is advised to parallelize your experiments,\n262:     as otherwise it may take months to run the experiments.\n263:     The benchmark currently only supports native parallelization in `aws` mode\n264:     (by using the `--parallel` parameter), but using the `--task` and `--fold` parameters\n265:     it is easy to generate scripts that invoke individual jobs on e.g., a SLURM cluster.\n266:     When you run in any parallelized fashion, it is advised to run each process on\n267:     separate hardware to ensure experiments can not interfere with each other.\n\n(End of file - total 267 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\ntitle: Getting Started\ndescription: A short tutorial on installing the software and running a simple benchmark.\n---\n\n# Getting Started\n\nThe AutoML Benchmark is a tool for benchmarking AutoML frameworks on tabular data.\nIt automates the installation of AutoML frameworks, passing it data, and evaluating\ntheir predictions.\n[Our paper](https://arxiv.org/pdf/2207.12560.pdf) describes the design and showcases\nresults from an evaluation using the benchmark.\nThis guide goes over the minimum steps needed to evaluate an\nAutoML framework on a toy dataset.\n\n## Installation\nThese instructions assume that [Python 3.9 (or higher)](https://www.python.org/downloads/)\nand [git](https://git-scm.com/book/en/v2/Getting-Started-Installing-Git) are installed,\nand are available under the alias `python` and `git`, respectively. We recommend\n[Pyenv](https://github.com/pyenv/pyenv) for managing multiple Python installations,","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"docs/getting_started.md","time":{"start":1775796240958,"end":1775796240965}}}]}
